  "chunk_index": 32,
  "summary": "During an investigation, Hakaste presents several clocks to Mrs. Melina Rival. She expresses interest in a gilded clock and notes that the man she married, Harry Castleton, appeared to be a respectable upper-class gentleman, which led her to fall in love with him. When asked about a connection to the name \"Rosemary,\" she recalls a redhead named Rosalie but cannot confirm a link to her husband. She also notes a clock's hands pointing to 4:13. Mrs. Rival agrees to provide identification for a trial in two days, stating she married Castleton over twenty years ago at St. Michael's Church in Dunbrooke. After she departs, Detective Inspector Gray arrives, and Hercule Poirot observes that Castleton’s respectable appearance is likely his modus operandi and suspects multiple women are seeking revenge against him. Poirot specifically ponders a clock inscribed with \"Rosemary.\"\n\nLater, Colin Lamb meets with Poirot, who is annoyed by renovations in his apartment building. They discuss the identification of the deceased in the Crocetta trial as Harry Castleton. Poirot notes that the wife, Mrs. Melina Rival, has been cooperative. The conversation shifts to a girl named Ina who died in a phone booth on Wilbraham Crescent; Poirot critiques Lamb's failure to gather specific details about her movements and the location of a grille where her heel became stuck. The following evening, Lamb meets with Hakaste at his house. Hakaste reveals that Harry Castleton was a man who appeared respectable but made a living by marrying or engaging wealthy, gullible women to gain control of their savings before disappearing.",
